, judge, and New York State Assemblyman — was one of the figures who helped organize the Republican Party in 1856 at its founding convention. He was an anti-slavery activist throughout his career. Their April 27, 1841 marriage came after Amelia's widowhood from her first husband Rev. Charles Jenkins of Greenfield Massachusetts."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Granddaughter of Yale President Ezra Stiles","body":"Amelia's mother Emilia Stiles was a daughter of Ezra Stiles — the President of Yale College from 1778 to 1795 — making Amelia a granddaughter of one of New England's most important late-eighteenth-century theological and academic figures. Her father Hon. Jonathan Leavitt was judge and businessman of Greenfield Massachusetts, and son of Sarah Hooker, putting Amelia at the intersection of the Yale-presidential and Hooker-descent lines."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Granddaughter of Sarah Hooker; born Greenfield 1799","body":"Amelia Stiles Leavitt was a granddaughter of Sarah Hooker through her father Hon. Jonathan Leavitt — Sarah had died eight years before Amelia's 1799 birth, so they never met. Amelia herself was born December 6, 1799 in Greenfield Massachusetts and died November 26, 1867 in New Haven Connecticut, where Dr. Foote had practiced medicine."}],"slug":"amelia-leavitt-1799"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}